and i do have faith that it will eventually be easier, but right now, it's harder than it's ever been for me. that's the truth of it.

these honest thoughts on recovery are never meant to discourage anyone. i share my experience because i don't want anyone else in recovery to feel alone, and also because setting up false expectations around recovery is arguably really harmful. it's so important to be realistic

i know people love to say that recovery isn't linear, but i feel like that's generally used to talk about relapses & using behaviours. but recovery is also non-linear in that it can be mentally easier early on but mentally much more challenging when you're further into it

i think it's because early recovery (involving weight gain) is "i have to eat this much to stay alive & heal my body" vs. later in recovery/once weight restored it's "i have to come to terms with being this large for the rest of my life, or at least as long as i'm in treatment"

in my experience, recovery is actually a lot easier (at least mentally) if/when you're weight restoring. continuing to recover in my "weight restored" body is 10x more challenging than when i was on a weight gain meal plan

lmao this is a long thread & tangent that started with a very simple question. anyways, tldr; when asking for gifts, check your privilege /hj

it's a good reminder that your perspective will be skewed based on your own life experience, family, class, etc. & that some of us (wealthier folks) should remember that most people aren't super wealthy. asking for expensive gifts is a sign of immense privilege, it really is

it's once again been really helpful for me to see people talking about how some of us on here (myself included) are incredibly privileged. i live in a bit of an economic/class "bubble"—i'm surrounded by wealthy people & families, including those much wealthier than my family

i don't want to just not acknowledge the fact that i am asking for some expensive things, it would feel odd to not mention that. however, a note: i do get most of my "nice"/expensive gifts at christmas, these are *definitely* not everyday purchases or gifts for me!!

and in reference to em's tweet (don't want this to be a subtweet, also /nm!!), i am upper-middle/upper-class, but even i don't expect to get all of this. the fact that i feel okay asking for this stuff is definitely a sign of privilege, and i feel incredibly grateful for that
and then the usual: skincare, lush products (especially bath bombs), books, socks, crystals/witchy shit, etc.

steps i'm taking to prevent a relapse into obsessive calorie-counting/food tracking:

• i haven't redownloaded mfp, i'm just using my notes app
• i'm only using estimations to get the grams of protein in my snacks & meals
• i'm rounding my numbers to be *less* precise about it

i'm doing this because i know i feel better when i'm eating more protein. i'm still allowing myself to eat foods that aren't protein-rich (fruits, cereal, desserts, some liquid cals, etc.), but having a protein goal (minimum 80g) really helps me eat enough protein
